        <p>
         		kō-vic<choice>
            <orig>a</orig>
            <reg>ai</reg>
          </choice>ya-tanti-vikkirama-parumaṟku yāṇṭu patt-āvatu
         	</p>
        <p>         		
         		kāliyū
         	</p>
      </div>
      <div type="apparatus">
        <listApp>
          <app loc="1">
            <lem>kāliyū</lem>
            <note>The inscription stops short here (<bibl>
                <ptr target="bib:SubrahmanyaAiyer1928_01"/>
                <citedRange unit="page">158</citedRange>
                <citedRange unit="note">1</citedRange>
              </bibl>). Evidently <foreign>kāliyūr-k-kōṭṭatu</foreign> was intended, followed presumably by <foreign>taṉ kūṟṟu Uttaramēru-c-catu<hi rend="grantha">rvve</hi>timaṅkalattu <hi rend="grantha">sabhai</hi>yōm</foreign> or a variant of it. Compare other inscriptions from Uttiramērūr.</note>
          </app>
        </listApp>
      </div>
      <div resp="part:emfr" type="translation">
        <p n="1">
      			Prosperity! Fortune!
      		</p>
        <p n="1">
      			Tenth year of the victorious king Dantivikramavarman.
      		</p>
        <p n="1">
      			<supplied reason="subaudible">in</supplied> the Kāliyū<supplied reason="subaudible">r-k-kōṭṭam</supplied></p>
